n -- t19. Uriderstanding Mondragόn’s Founder -- t20. Ethnic and Organizational Cultures -- t21. Implications of the Mondragόn Experience -- tAppendix. Evolution of Our Research on Mondragόn -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince its founding in 1956 in Spain's Basque region, the Mondragón Corporation has been a touchstone for the international cooperative movement. Its nearly three hundred companies and organizations span areas from finance to education. In its industrial sector Mondragón has had a rich experience over many years in manufacturing products as varied as furniture, kitchen equipment, machine tools, and electronic components and in printing, shipbuilding, and metal smelting.Making Mondragón is a groundbreaking look at the history of worker ownership in the Spanish cooperative. First published in 1988, it remains the best source for those looking to glean a rich body of ideas for potential adaptation and implementation elsewhere from Mondragón's long and varied experience. This second edition, published in 1991, takes into account the major structural and strategic changes that were being implemented in 1990 to allow the enterprise to compete successfully in the European common market.Mondragón has created social inventions and developed social structures and social processes that have enabled it to overcome some of the major obstacles faced by other worker cooperatives in the past. William Foote Whyte and Kathleen King Whyte describe the creation and evolution of the Mondragón cooperatives, how they have changed through decades of experience, and how they have struggled to maintain a balance between their social commitments and economic realities. The lessons of Mondragón apply most clearly to worker cooperatives and other employee-owned firms, but also extend to regional development and stimulating and supporting entrepreneurship, whatever the form of ownership.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aProducer cooperativeszSpainzMondragón. 4aEurope. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aAdministrative Science.  aAmerican social science.  aContemporary Sociology.  aMondragÃ³n Corporation.  aOrganization Studies.  aOrganizational Development european.  aSpanish cooperative.  acommunity economic development.  acooperative employee ownership.  acooperative enterprise.  aemployee-owned firms.  aeuropean politics.  aeuropean worker relations.  aevolution of the MondragÃ³n cooperatives.  ahow to create a worker cooperative.  ainterest in worker cooperatives.  ainternational cooperative movement.  alabor relations case studies.  alabor relations.  aorganizational Sociology.  aorganizational practice.  aorganizational sociologists.  aorganizational theorists.  aqualitative methodologists of American social science.  aqualitative methodologists.  asocial anthropology of advanced organizations.  asocial scientists of administration.  aspanish business practices.  aspanish worker relations.  awork redesign programs.  aworker cooperative .  aworker cooperatives.1 aWhyte, Kathleen King, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147173540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471735423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801471735/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3